===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|pli||lang=frm|pleat, fold}}, from {{term|plier||lang=frm|bend, fold}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|plico||lang=la|fold, fold together}}

====Noun====
{{en-noun|pl|ies}}

# A [[layer]] of material. (''two-ply toilet paper'')
# A [[strand]] that, twisted together with other strands, makes up [[yarn]] or [[rope]].
# {{colloquial}} [[plywood|Plywood]].
# {{context|artificial intelligence|game theory}} In two-player sequential games, a "half-turn", or one move made by one of the players.
#: ''He proposed to build 'Deep Purple' a super-computer capable of 24-'''ply''' look-ahead for chess.''
# {{context|now|_|chiefly|_|Scotland}} [[state|State]], [[condition]].
#* '''1749''', John Cleland, ''Memoirs of a Woman of Pleasure'', Penguin 1985, p. 66:
#*: You may be sure, in the '''ply''' I was now taking, I had no objection to the proposal, and was rather a-tiptoe for its accomplishment.

